{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d0d317e-09f4-4aff-8c3d-bbf82850264c","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool). On macOS you rely on the OS-level crash reporting:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name/timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>` (macOS default).\n\n3. **If `/cores` is missing or SIP blocks it**, create and set permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For .NET-specific managed state**, you can load the SOS/dotnet-dump plugin in `lldb`, though NativeAOT has limited SOS support compared to CoreCLR.\n\n**Key point:** On macOS, the OS crash reporter is your primary mechanism — `createdump` was never expected to be available for NativeAOT workloads.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"77979da2-237d-4b78-b37b-dd0ea09d6940","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"CB00:392B11:70D73D:815B00:6A052A37"},"id":"d89a2a68-61bf-489d-920b-948dc0df6738","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:49:54.214Z","parentId":"358b0299-6b81-449e-b472-be05b96f9713"}
